           <a><a/><p><font color = "#ff0000">One of the most challenging elements of colonizing Mars is the danger of radiation. Both the attempt to reach the surface of Mars and the surface of Mars itself would expose explorers to extremely high levels of radiation from which they would need to be continually protected to avoid diseases such as cancer.  There are two primary sources of radiation – the sun and galactic cosmic rays. Space vehicles and suits can protect astronauts from the first source. However, protons from galactic cosmic rays have more energy and can pierce both the suits and metals such as spacecraft or habitats or other vehicles.</font></p>
			  
			  
			  
            <p><font color = "#ff0000">NASA has already begun to develop a human mission to Mars which they are planning to launch by the early 2030’s. This would entail landing astronauts on Martian soil – and supporting them by providing all the means of survival while they are there.  Because of significant radiation, however, technology will need to be developed to provide shielded housing for the astronauts. But not just for astronauts.  Equipment must also be shielded.  Scientists have already begun to explore the idea of building radiation storm shelters and also building force fields to create a safe bubble around spacecraft and habitats.</font></p>
			
			<center>
