			<center>
			<p><font style = "color:#ff0000; font-size: 30px;">" Force field building bubble around spacecraft and equipment"</font></p>
			</center>
			
			
			
            <p><font color = "#ff0000">Every aspect of the journey and inhabitation of Mars would need to be shielded from the ever-present danger.  In fact, the trip to Mars is far more dangerous regarding radiation than life on the planet would be. The trip itself would expose astronauts to six months of a radiation shower. The average dose of radiation for this journey would equal 24 CAT scans, 15 times the annual radiation limit for nuclear power plant workers. Even on Mars itself, while radiation exposure would be reduced, it would vary widely weekly, monthly, and seasonally.</font></p>
			
            <p><font color = "#ff0000">In addition, bio-medical advances will be necessary to deal with any radiation the astronauts might experience. The dangers are serious – changes to their DNA, cataracts, changes to the brain and nervous system, cancer and radiation sickness which can lead to death.  In addition to protecting astronauts, scientists are thinking through the possibility of developing a medication that would counteract exposure to radiation – something that would make the trip to Mars and living on Mars less dangerous.</font></p>
			
			
            <p><font color = "#ff0000">There are also some ideas that border on science fiction but may not be beyond the realm of possibility.  One of these is to create and launch a giant magnetic shield to protect Mars from excess radiation from solar winds, making water flow on Mars’ surface and making Mars far more habitable.  A second idea is to change the human genome, a 500-year project suggested by Christopher Mason, so that injury to genes caused by radiation could be constantly repaired. A third possibility is to land on Phobos, Mars’ largest moon, to collect water lurking just below the surface and use that water to fill the elastic cells in the spacecraft which would also shield astronauts from radiation.</font></p>
			
